title: For Sale:  Charles Daly 1911 - make offer
postcontent:
For sale (not really needing a trade at this time) is my Charles Daly 1911.  This model is not made anymore as far as I know.  Too heavy for me to carry and too beautiful for a range gun.  Need room in safe and money for projects.

Gun has polished sides, jeweled (swirled) metalwork on bushing, mag release, hammer, grip safety, exposed barrell, and trigger.  Has extended ambi safety, novak style sights, and skeletonized trigger and hammer.  Does not look tacky or like a Bling piece.  

The total effect is tasteful and unique.  You will not find another like it.  It will really turn heads.  I wore it open carry to a swap meet one time and had numerous offers for cash that I should have taken but the gun was still new to me.

Gun shoots great.  It is reliable and accurate.  It shows very little wear (less than 500 rounds).  Trigger has been worked and breaks clean.  Comes with 4 grips (wood, black rubber, hogue wraparound, and black pearl), and 3 mags.  There is a a light idiot scratch on it, but otherwise it is nearly perfect.

Make me an offer.  I have $650 invested in this gun and I don't think I need to lose money, but we will see what offers I get.  Please no lo-ballers.

title: For Trade:  Springfield 1911-A1 GI 45acp for revolver
postcontent:
Looking to trade this excellent condition Springfield 1911 GI.  As a lefty I just have to face the fact that the 1911 just doesn't do it for me*.  This gun is in fantastic shape.  I am the original owner, round count is 300.  Pistol will come with all factory items and manual, one magazine.  Local trades only.

I'm looking to trade this for a revolver in .327 Federal, .32 H&R, 44 Special, 44 Mag, 45 acp or 45 Colt, or other 45 automatics.  I am not interested in single action revolvers unless it is a 45 Colt Ruger Super Blackhawk Hunter model.
This list isn't all inclusive of what I'm looking for, but it's a start.  I'm not really interested in Charter Arms except the old model Bulldogs

.32 H&R or .327--S&W 632, 631, Ruger SP101, S&W 16-4
44 Special--Any S&W
44 Mag--Any S&W, the shorter the better
45 Colt-- S&W, Ruger, or Taurus DA that isn't a Judge
45 ACP--S&W or Taurus DA
.357--S&W pre-lock with 3" or shorter barrel.
.22lr--Any S&W

Maybe Ruger SA 44 specials if they have a holster and a couple boxes of ammo. 


For semi-auto handguns, I'm looking for
S&W 4506, 4505, CS45, 4566, 4586, 645, 745, 4516
S&W 1006, 1076, 1026, 1066
Full size M&P 45
Full size XD(m) 45
Sig P220


No hunting rifles, shotguns or .40's.
Not interested in polymer guns, not interested in Taurus Judges
FTF only in St. Louis.  MO residents only.



*  Yes, I am aware that there are ambidextrous safeties for 1911's.  I've tried them of several 1911's and just never felt confident with them.  They always have had a bit of play in them that I didn't care for.  As such, I'm letting my last 1911 go.

title: For Sale/Trade:  FN HiPower
postcontent:
For sale is my FN HiPower in 9mm Luger, $800 + shipping or trade for the below.

This pistol is from one of the first production runs out of FN after Liege was liberated from the Germans, assembled from parts produced under German occupation but with all Liege/Allied markings (no German stamping of any sort).

After speaking with someone from FN, more information has come to light about this particular Hi Power as to the origin dates. Based on the serial number, it was probably produced in late '44 or early '45. Smooth top slide, no rib, GI sights. Serial number is A60xx -- four digit with A series prefix.

As I understand it from someone who is a euro gun expert, not me, the slide was an arsenal replacement at some point later on which is why it includes an external extractor. It was then used by the Austrian police service or Austrian military police (If I recall correctly from the roll marks).

I'm in no hurry to sell this as I don't really need the money, this is just for my fun fund. I picked this up from Todd at FF&F a few years back and just never rotate it into carry or really shoot it at shoots. As we all know, I don't keep guns I don't regularly (or at least semi-regularly) shoot.

Includes one serial number matching 13rd FN (extremely rare type magazine with split tongue baseplate), two non-matching 13rd FN OEM mags, and two 15rd MecGar mags, Spegel style grips and original WWII grips, Israeli 1911 holster modified to fit the Hi Power, and a Hunter leather holster that fits it rather well.

title: For Sale:  1941 RARE SVT-40, early style brake, w/ sling and rod
postcontent:
For sale is a WWII Soviet SVT-40 made in 1941 by Tula. It fires the very common 7.62 x 54r cartridge.  These rifles are very hard to find as many were lost or captured at the start of the war and what ones were left aren't currently being imported to the United States.

It is a typical refurb in that the bolt and carrier have been blued.  It sits in an AVT stock, which is very common for refurbs as the standard SVT stocks had problems with cracking.  

-Has rails on side of receiver for scope mount
-Does not have notch in top of receiver for scope mount clip
-Has later style one-piece front sling swivel
-Has earlier-style "bird-cage" muzzle brake
-Correct Russian sling, green canvas
-Numbers matching with exception of magazine, some force matched (electropenciled)
-Dark bore with strong rifling, very typical of whats available on the market
-One arsenal stock repair, hardly noticeable
-Includes reproduction gas tube adjustment tool

(Nintendo cart in pictures is just a "timestamp" of sorts)

Looking to do a FTF transfer, cash only.  I'm located right at the border of Kansas and Missouri so I don't mind traveling to meet up as long as my fuel costs are considered.  Send me a message and we can go from there.
